1	\chapter{The Abel--Jacobi map}
2	\label{chap:AbelJacobi}
3	
4	Let $C$ be a smooth proper curve over $k$ as in Chapter~\ref{chap:Genus}, and let $\Jac(C)$ be its Jacobian (Definition~\ref{def:Jacobian}).
5	
6	\section{Definition}
7	
8	\begin{definition}[Abel--Jacobi map]
9	  \label{def:ofCurve}
10	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.ofCurve}
11	  \uses{def:Jacobian}
12	  Given a $k$-rational point $P \colon \Spec k \to C$ --- equivalently, a morphism $P \colon \mathbf 1 \to C$ in the category of $k$-schemes --- the \emph{Abel--Jacobi map} is the $k$-morphism
13	  \[
14	    \alpha_P \colon C \;\longrightarrow\; \Jac(C),\qquad Q \;\longmapsto\; [\mathcal O_C(Q - P)].
15	  \]
16	  Functorially, it is the morphism in the category of $k$-schemes induced by the line bundle $\mathcal O_{C \times C}(\Delta - p_1^* P)$ on $C \times C$ via the universal property of $\Pic^0_{C/k}$.
17	\end{definition}
18	
19	\section{Pointed property}
20	
21	\begin{lemma}[$\alpha_P$ sends $P$ to $0$]
22	  \label{lem:comp_ofCurve}
23	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.comp_ofCurve}
24	  \uses{def:ofCurve}
25	  $P \;\circ\; \alpha_P \;=\; \eta[\Jac(C)]$, where $\eta[\Jac(C)]$ is the identity element of the group scheme $\Jac(C)$.
26	\end{lemma}
27	
28	\begin{proof}
29	  \uses{def:ofCurve}
30	  At the level of $k$-points: $\alpha_P(P) = [\mathcal O_C(P - P)] = [\mathcal O_C] = 0$. Globally: by construction, $\alpha_P$ is the morphism classifying the line bundle $\mathcal O_{C \times C}(\Delta - p_1^* P)$; restricting to the section $(P, \mathrm{id})$ gives the trivial line bundle, hence the zero point of $\Pic^0$.
31	\end{proof}
32	
33	\section{Universal (Albanese) property}
34	
35	\begin{theorem}[Albanese property of the Jacobian]
36	  \label{thm:exists_unique_ofCurve_comp}
37	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.exists_unique_ofCurve_comp}
38	  \uses{def:ofCurve, lem:comp_ofCurve}
39	  Let $A$ be an abelian variety over $k$ --- i.e.\ a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme over $k$. For every pointed morphism $f \colon C \to A$ with $f \circ P = \eta[A]$, there exists a unique group-scheme morphism $g \colon \Jac(C) \to A$ such that $f = g \circ \alpha_P$.
40	  \[
41	  \begin{array}{ccc}
42	    C & \stackrel{f}{\longrightarrow} & A \\
43	    {\scriptstyle\alpha_P} \downarrow & \nearrow {\scriptstyle\exists ! g} & \\
44	    \Jac(C) & &
45	  \end{array}
46	  \]
47	\end{theorem}
48	
49	\begin{proof}
50	  \uses{def:IsAlbanese, thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness, thm:IsAlbanese_unique}
51	  The Jacobian is constructed precisely so that it is an Albanese object for $(C, P)$: by Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}, applied with the marked point $P$, there exists a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme $J$ over $k$ of dimension $g(C)$ together with a morphism $\iota_P \colon C \to J$ with $\iota_P \circ P = \eta_J$, and the pair $(J, \iota_P)$ satisfies the Albanese universal property of Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese}. The chosen Albanese object is $\Jac(C)$, and the universal morphism is the Abel--Jacobi map $\alpha_P$ of Definition~\ref{def:ofCurve}; by construction $\alpha_P = \iota_P$.
52	
53	  Existence and uniqueness of the factorisation $g$ are then exactly the universal-property data carried by $\iota_P$ in Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese}: for every pointed $f \colon C \to A$ with $f \circ P = \eta_A$, there exists a unique $g \colon J \to A$ with $f = \iota_P \circ g$.
54	
55	  In the genus-$0$ case, $\Jac(C) = \Spec k$ is the terminal object in the category of $k$-schemes over $\Spec k$, so every morphism into the trivial group scheme is uniquely determined by its source.
56	\end{proof}
57	
58	\section{Implementation route via the Albanese framework}
59	
60	The three results above are formalised through the Albanese framework of Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian}. In the absence of Mathlib's Pic-scheme machinery, the Jacobian is defined as an Albanese object of $(C, P)$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}); the universal-property data $(\iota_P, \text{factorisation})$ is then carried by the Albanese predicate (Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese}) and projects directly into the three results of this chapter. Existence of an Albanese object is the single remaining mathematical hypothesis pending the formalisation of either Pic-scheme representability or symmetric-power quotients in Mathlib.
61	
62	The classical proof via line bundles --- using the universal property of $\Pic^0_{C/k}$, dual abelian varieties, and the rigidity theorem of Mumford \S4 --- gives the same conclusion but requires more Mathlib infrastructure (dual abelian varieties, biduality, generation of $\Jac(C)$ by the image of $\alpha_P$, the rigidity theorem). The Albanese-framework route used here is mathematically equivalent and avoids all of these obstructions.
63

